sentences: Miriam Beatrice Hyde  (15 January 1913 – 11 January 2005) was an Australian composer, mainly classical, pianist, music educator and poet.
Hyde was born in Adelaide in 1913.
Her early music lessons were provided by her mother, but in 1925 she won a scholarship to attend the Elder Conservatorium of Music in Adelaide.
After graduating with her Bachelor of Music degree in 1931, she won an Elder Scholarship to the Royal College of Music in London, which she attended from 1932 to 1935.

In 1935, she performed Beethoven's Piano Concerto No. 4 under Malcolm Sargent, and her own Piano Concerto No. 2 with the London Symphony Orchestra conducted by Constant Lambert.
She returned to Adelaide in 1936 and soon after moved to Sydney, where she worked for several decades as a composer, recitalist, teacher, examiner and lecturer.

Her work for the Australian Music Examinations Board (AMEB) spanned the years 1945–82, including her valuable contribution on the Advisory Board for New South Wales.
In 1981 she was made an Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE) and in 1991 was made an Officer of the Order of Australia (AO).

After serving on the Council of the Music Teachers' Association of New South Wales from 1960 to 1991, she was made its patron.
In 1991 her autobiography was published, titled Complete Accord.
She celebrated her 80th birthday in 1993 by giving a series of recitals throughout the country.
Her 90th birthday in 2003 was marked with concerts and broadcasts throughout Australia.
